1
00:00:03,305 --> 00:00:16,663
The Five Spiritual Faculties For the past few evenings we've been exploring the Brahma Vihara which described the ways wisdom is expressed in our relationship with others.

2
00:00:17,844 --> 00:00:25,414
Tonight I want to take a step back into our individual psyche and look at the strengths that develop from our practice.

3
00:00:26,760 --> 00:00:36,732
These are described as the five spiritual faculties and they are mindfulness, energy, concentration, faith and wisdom.

4
00:00:38,014 --> 00:00:47,225
We mentioned these already in relation to the seven factors of enlightenment and this talk also provides a bit of revision on these factors that develop as we meditate.

5
00:00:48,966 --> 00:00:50,929
Remember the wild geese analogy?

6
00:00:51,887 --> 00:01:02,529
Mindfulness was in the lead, followed in the slipstream by a calming trio, headed up by concentration and then following on were equanimity and tranquility.

7
00:01:03,850 --> 00:01:10,504
Pressing ahead on the wide flank were the stimulating factors of energy, investigation and joy.

8
00:01:12,087 --> 00:01:18,671
The leading trio of mindfulness, concentration and energy have joined us again in the spiritual faculties.

9
00:01:19,715 --> 00:01:23,007
This time they are accompanied by wisdom and faith.

10
00:01:25,468 --> 00:01:43,528
The seven factors describe the skills used during Vipassana, while the spiritual faculties describe the strengths built from our meditation practice and which can then be used in daily life or during challenges in meditation when equanimity, joy and tranquility desert us.

11
00:01:44,650 --> 00:01:46,093
Let's take an example.

12
00:01:47,153 --> 00:01:51,981
Suppose you're at the social welfare office to find out why your payment hasn't arrived this month.

13
00:01:53,043 --> 00:01:57,974
The person you normally deal with has been transferred and the newcomer can't find your file.

14
00:01:57,993 --> 00:02:04,585
After consulting with others, he shrugs his shoulders and says, you'll have to reapply for all your benefits.

15
00:02:06,028 --> 00:02:09,194
A button pops inside you and rage boils up.

16
00:02:11,318 --> 00:02:14,866
Which of the seven factors will come to your aid in this situation?

17
00:02:16,031 --> 00:02:24,211
Your mind won't be equanimous, tranquil or joyful, and you won't be investigating the transitory nature of experience.

18
00:02:24,231 --> 00:02:27,842
Thus, four of the seven factors of enlightenment are missing.

19
00:02:28,986 --> 00:02:44,468
But you can be mindful and focus your full attention on the interaction with the official, while summoning the energy needed to prevent yourself throttling the officer who is smiling innocuously, happy to have ticked off another client from his list.

20
00:02:47,413 --> 00:02:50,456
Thus, we still have the three leaders in the wild geese.

21
00:02:51,239 --> 00:02:54,402
Mindfulness, concentration and energy.

22
00:02:55,766 --> 00:03:00,234
To back these up, you could remind yourself that speaking out of anger never helps.

23
00:03:01,735 --> 00:03:07,324
This is your accumulated store of wisdom, calming the storm of passion that's exploding within you.

24
00:03:08,847 --> 00:03:12,651
You might also be encouraging yourself that things will work out somehow.

25
00:03:14,155 --> 00:03:22,467
This is the faith or confidence that accrues from practice and helps us see the silver lining within the storm clouds.

26
00:03:24,842 --> 00:03:34,187
So the spiritual faculties are the benefits that accrue from honing the seven factors of enlightenment.

27
00:03:34,207 --> 00:03:35,510
Here is an analogy.

28
00:03:36,638 --> 00:03:43,086
A nice skater would use skills like balance, physical strength, grace and expressivity while skating.

29
00:03:44,487 --> 00:03:51,776
Some of these, like strength and grace for example, will accumulate as personal capacities that are useful in daily life.

30
00:03:53,018 --> 00:04:02,409
The skater's off-ice life will also benefit from related offshoots such as physical fitness and the confidence that comes from developing a skill.

31
00:04:04,701 --> 00:04:17,326
Just as ice skating requires a very special set of skills and circumstances, the factors of enlightenment describe the skills involved in maintaining the pretty exalted state we achieve in Vipassana.

32
00:04:18,843 --> 00:04:24,408
But the accumulated strengths from both activities help us in a very down-to-earth way.

33
00:04:25,889 --> 00:04:36,300
Thus the spiritual faculties provide the qualities we need to turn our welfare office encounter and all aspects of ordinary daily life into a spiritual practice.

34
00:04:37,822 --> 00:04:46,250
They also come to the fore during turgid, unexalted times in formal meditation while we're threading our way through the hindrances.

35
00:04:50,990 --> 00:04:58,586
Let's go through the five spiritual faculties in more detail and look especially at how to apply these during challenges.

36
00:05:00,509 --> 00:05:10,550
Mindfulness describes our capacity to be conscious of present moment experience such as physical sensations, sounds, sights, emotions and thoughts.

37
00:05:11,661 --> 00:05:23,293
Although this capacity is natural, we generally ignore whatever is impacting on our senses and instead follow the dictates of whatever thoughts we concoct in our busy minds.

38
00:05:24,613 --> 00:05:33,401
During meditation, we train ourselves to experience life at a simpler level than that engendered by the filter of thoughts and beliefs.

39
00:05:36,125 --> 00:05:41,550
In meditation, we usually start by placing attention on the physical sensations of breathing.

40
00:05:42,745 --> 00:05:46,672
Then we might notice the pleasure of relaxing from our usual busyness.

41
00:05:48,235 --> 00:05:59,774
Bringing the pleasure centre stage, we might see that it has the emotional tone of contentment alongside pleasurable physical sensations associated with relaxation.

42
00:06:01,307 --> 00:06:13,269
After a while we may grow sleepy, so we broaden our attention to notice our posture and the sensations that register as we straighten the spine to prevent ourselves falling asleep.

43
00:06:14,752 --> 00:06:24,970
In all this we are honing the skill of mindfulness, training our minds to register present experience rather than be ensnared in our mental concoctions.

44
00:06:27,785 --> 00:06:34,031
One strength that builds from this training is a capacity to see through our mental filters in daily life.

45
00:06:35,209 --> 00:06:43,463
In our welfare office scenario, the faculty of mindfulness will help us register rage as part of the objective reality of the situation.

46
00:06:44,625 --> 00:06:50,995
Without mindfulness the rage would take us over and our minds would only see reality through its filter.

47
00:06:52,317 --> 00:07:00,492
Thus the official would, in our minds, become horrible, lazy, incompetent and all the other labels rage places upon him.

48
00:07:01,535 --> 00:07:08,163
we might suddenly realise that the whole welfare system is unfair, infuriating, stupid, etc.

49
00:07:09,505 --> 00:07:14,273
Our speech and behaviour will then follow the habit pattern we've built up to deal with conflict.

50
00:07:15,535 --> 00:07:24,286
For some, this will mean banging fists on the counter or bellowing into the ears of the official, giving them a perfect excuse to refuse to deal with this further.

51
00:07:25,809 --> 00:07:30,175
For others, it would mean channelling all the emotional energy into assertiveness.

52
00:07:31,487 --> 00:07:45,007
For others it could mean a collapse into livid despair as we take the forms home to commence the wearying search for documents all the time cursing the official and the system and whatever else crosses our path.

53
00:07:47,872 --> 00:07:52,278
With mindfulness we will feel the surge of rage as it surfaces.

54
00:07:53,581 --> 00:08:01,291
While all the nasty labels may get stamped on the official and the situation there is also some objectivity about these

55
00:08:02,673 --> 00:08:05,235
We know that our vision and thoughts are being coloured.

56
00:08:06,757 --> 00:08:09,341
This gives us some choice in what happens next.

57
00:08:10,663 --> 00:08:15,689
For example, we could decide to take a few mindful breaths to help us calm down a bit.

58
00:08:16,910 --> 00:08:23,617
If we've done a lot of practice, we'll be able to acknowledge some of the complexity of emotions and feelings being generated.

59
00:08:24,896 --> 00:08:35,009
There may be a physical tension in our face or throat, our eyes may be popping, our brow is furrowed, our jaw stiff.

60
00:08:35,029 --> 00:08:41,057
There may be the heady buzz that energises us in conflict situations and a strong sense of self.

61
00:08:42,499 --> 00:08:51,629
To the extent that these are registered consciously, their hold over us is reduced and the ill-will driving our response is tempered.

62
00:08:55,475 --> 00:09:12,504
While the Dhamma doesn't give us any prescription for how to deal with conflicting situations like this, mindfulness allows us learn our own unique best strategy to find pathways which transform the energy of anger into assertiveness.

63
00:09:14,240 --> 00:09:27,357
although the ingrained reactionary habit might still be 99% in control of the situation, we have that 1% of mindfulness reminding us of anger as part of the objective reality.

64
00:09:29,941 --> 00:09:37,510
And even if our behaviour follows its usual route, we will at some stage be able to reflect on the situation and learn some lessons.

65
00:09:40,655 --> 00:09:43,099
Let's now look at the faculty of concentration.

66
00:09:44,716 --> 00:09:48,221
This is not the furrowed brow concentration required for school work.

67
00:09:49,543 --> 00:09:55,611
It refers to our ability to select out some aspect of experience and rest attention there.

68
00:09:57,514 --> 00:10:01,120
There are two levels of concentration which are of particular interest here.

69
00:10:02,722 --> 00:10:06,589
The first describes a mind that is approaching its focus.

70
00:10:07,767 --> 00:10:24,109
In meditation we might be encouraging ourselves to focus on the sensations of breathing, aware of lots of other sensations, feelings and the mind state in the background, but centring our attention on the breath.

71
00:10:24,129 --> 00:10:33,522
The analogy used to describe this is a bee hovering around a flower, following it back and forth in the breeze, waiting for the right moment to alight.

72
00:10:35,375 --> 00:10:40,081
This type of concentration is termed vitaka or applied thought.

73
00:10:41,361 --> 00:10:45,907
The word thought here does not mean that we think about the sensations of breathing.

74
00:10:47,109 --> 00:10:52,254
It means we bring our intelligence and curiosity to bear on these sensations.

75
00:10:56,058 --> 00:11:04,369
At the next level of concentration, termed vichara or sustained thought, the bee has landed and is sucking nectar.

76
00:11:05,107 --> 00:11:07,412
This type of concentration is more restful.

77
00:11:08,072 --> 00:11:10,777
We're no longer making the effort to keep our mind steady.

78
00:11:11,879 --> 00:11:14,743
We're now absorbed in the experience of breathing.

79
00:11:17,386 --> 00:11:23,576
Concentration works hand in hand with mindfulness, giving the mind a specific focus for awareness.

80
00:11:24,298 --> 00:11:27,403
For example, the sensations of breathing or walking.

81
00:11:29,475 --> 00:11:36,966
These sensations provide a good resting place for the mind during formal meditation and also during quiet moments in daily life.

82
00:11:38,467 --> 00:11:42,594
This helps us to let go of the stress that easily builds up during ordinary life.

83
00:11:44,196 --> 00:11:50,504
But in situations where we need to be actively engaged, it's a good habit to be more broadly aware.

84
00:11:50,788 --> 00:11:58,999
Very often the external situation we find ourselves in provides sufficient draw for our attention, so concentration happens quite naturally.

85
00:11:59,940 --> 00:12:14,417
For example, while we are actually talking to the official in the welfare office, our minds will be quite focused on the exchange, so we don't need to use any noting word or phrase to remind ourselves to be aware of present experience.

86
00:12:14,397 --> 00:12:17,301
This is the equivalent of vichara in Vipassana.

87
00:12:18,123 --> 00:12:23,029
We are absorbed within the experience and do not need to encourage our minds to focus.

88
00:12:25,072 --> 00:12:32,845
But in idle moments the mind might wander, for example, while waiting in the queue or while the official was searching for a file.

89
00:12:34,140 --> 00:12:44,764
Just as in formal meditation, when we wake up and notice we've been wandering, we can simply remind ourselves of what's going on and encourage ourselves to keep coming back to that reality.

90
00:12:46,067 --> 00:12:50,277
You could simply focus on sensations which will have a calming effect.

91
00:12:50,475 --> 00:12:54,982
But if you tend to be dreamy, it could help to remind yourself of the job at hand.

92
00:12:56,205 --> 00:13:05,679
A broad brush phrase like welfare office, asking why no benefit received, could be used to marshal your energies for the job at hand.

93
00:13:07,123 --> 00:13:09,947
It will need a degree of effort to keep the mind focused.

94
00:13:10,648 --> 00:13:16,197
So this is the daily life equivalent of Vittaka or applied thought in Vipassana.

95
00:13:18,774 --> 00:13:28,431
It is worthwhile reflecting on the fact that we mostly don't use a phrase like welfare office asking why no benefit received to help us through our day.

96
00:13:29,962 --> 00:13:38,611
This reflects the preference for our minds to drift and autopilot, rather than make conscious decisions and be mindful as we carry out our decisions.

97
00:13:39,734 --> 00:13:44,818
In effect, this lets us ignore the underlying motivations for much of our daily lives.

98
00:13:46,100 --> 00:13:54,570
For example, our trip to the welfare office might have followed automatically from annoyance that the usual payment hadn't been received.

99
00:13:54,549 --> 00:14:03,019
We will be carrying that annoyance unwittingly into the office and it will probably show up as an edge to our voice as we explain the problem.

100
00:14:04,320 --> 00:14:11,346
This is a form of aggression and in turn the official will react to that becoming less sympathetic to our case.

101
00:14:14,090 --> 00:14:20,135
Using a noting word in Vipassana sharpens our perceptions and helps us to see things in more detail.

102
00:14:21,230 --> 00:14:29,745
Similarly, noting phrases such as welfare office asking why no benefit received will sharpen our perceptions in daily life.

103
00:14:30,869 --> 00:14:33,934
This way we will notice the emotional baggage driving us.

104
00:14:35,577 --> 00:14:39,846
This brings us to the third of the spiritual faculties, energy.

105
00:14:41,648 --> 00:14:44,592
We'll have noticed the anger driving us to the welfare office.

106
00:14:45,335 --> 00:14:46,557
Is that a good enough motive?

107
00:14:47,519 --> 00:14:50,344
Hopefully we'll have enough wisdom to say no.

108
00:14:51,485 --> 00:14:55,573
To relinquish the anger we need the faculty of energy.

109
00:14:57,717 --> 00:15:02,626
The spiritual faculty of energy is the momentum behind right effort.

110
00:15:03,653 --> 00:15:12,106
For spiritual progress, we need to make the effort to undermine unskillful qualities like anger and develop skillful ones like metta.

111
00:15:13,227 --> 00:15:15,812
It takes enormous energy to make these changes.

112
00:15:17,134 --> 00:15:21,461
An apt metaphor of the Buddha gives is that of swimming upstream.

113
00:15:23,485 --> 00:15:26,789
We're continually having to work against our ingrained conditioning.

114
00:15:28,613 --> 00:15:31,197
We practice swimming upstream in Vipassana.

115
00:15:31,615 --> 00:15:35,841
No matter how often the mind wanders, we refuse to give up.

116
00:15:35,860 --> 00:15:36,601
We start again.

117
00:15:36,642 --> 00:15:41,590
No matter how sleepy we feel, we resist the temptation to lie down.

118
00:15:42,951 --> 00:15:54,248
Each time we make those efforts to start again, to keep the sleepy eyes open, to resist the urge to fidget, we are strengthening our spiritual faculty of energy.

119
00:15:57,602 --> 00:16:06,578
One benefit from all this hard work is that in daily life we will have the energy to undermine old habits, for example on the way to the welfare office.

120
00:16:08,042 --> 00:16:11,327
Seeing the anger driving us is already to undermine it.

121
00:16:12,711 --> 00:16:21,687
Anger may be churning within making our blood boil, but so long as it's contained within the gaze of awareness it can't do any harm.

122
00:16:22,932 --> 00:16:25,495
We can then choose a skilful motive for our trip.

123
00:16:26,136 --> 00:16:30,143
For example, may I look after myself well in this situation?

124
00:16:31,725 --> 00:16:35,330
This lets the whole sorry business become part of our spiritual life.

125
00:16:37,273 --> 00:16:40,979
It will help us appreciate any positives in the situation.

126
00:16:42,321 --> 00:16:49,311
Our friendly outlook may even touch into the heart of officialdom to motivate them to make a more thorough search for our file.

127
00:16:50,775 --> 00:16:56,754
Even if the outcome is exactly the same, we will have undermined our habit of acting out of anger.

128
00:16:57,837 --> 00:17:01,950
So the encounter will have been a rich one in terms of our spiritual life.

129
00:17:04,646 --> 00:17:15,752
To recap, the faculty of mindfulness honed during Vipassana as we bring our minds back again and again to present experience gives us a degree of objectivity in our daily life.

130
00:17:16,974 --> 00:17:21,204
The faculty of concentration gathers our often scattered attention

131
00:17:21,184 --> 00:17:28,959
So that instead of jumping all over the place or only vaguely aware of what we're doing, we can focus on each task in hand.

132
00:17:29,920 --> 00:17:34,989
As we do so, mindfulness lets our underlying motivations become more apparent.

133
00:17:36,412 --> 00:17:45,488
The faculty of energy then comes to the fore, resisting the strong current of unskillfulness, swimming upstream with skillful good wishes.

134
00:17:47,509 --> 00:17:54,541
With the three faculties working together, they simplify life and bring out the best in all situations.

135
00:17:55,983 --> 00:18:10,107
The autopilot mind tends to complicate things, building monsters and fairy tales in every idle moment, stoking our underlying and unacknowledged passions, poisoning the attitude with which we approach others.

136
00:18:11,319 --> 00:18:13,503
while we're waiting in the queue at the welfare office.

137
00:18:14,525 --> 00:18:20,555
Annoyance could be prompting grandiose plans of how we would reorganise the system if only we were in charge.

138
00:18:21,355 --> 00:18:28,468
If we don't notice this, we'll unwittingly be carrying our annoyance and disapproval into the encounter with the official.

139
00:18:29,426 --> 00:18:39,977
But if we wake up and remind ourselves of our present reality, welfare office, asking why payment not received, this has the effect of focusing the mind.

140
00:18:41,038 --> 00:18:47,644
Thus the energy of anger is transformed to assertiveness and channelled into a rightful business.

141
00:18:48,805 --> 00:18:57,814
If we can then add a good wish such as, may I look after myself happily, we'll achieve the crowning glory of a positive outlook.

142
00:19:01,067 --> 00:19:04,291
Now let's look at the faculties of faith and wisdom.

143
00:19:06,233 --> 00:19:11,339
Wisdom lets us discern which motivations are helpful and which are unskillful.

144
00:19:12,461 --> 00:19:17,748
Wisdom would remind us, acting out of anger doesn't help in that welfare office.

145
00:19:19,470 --> 00:19:24,155
We might undervalue such an obvious statement thinking, well everyone knows that.

146
00:19:25,156 --> 00:19:31,023
But if everyone knew that, there wouldn't be petty squabbles or gang feuds or murders.

147
00:19:31,949 --> 00:19:41,061
It's one thing to know that acting out of anger doesn't help when we're calmly reflecting on life in the comfort of home, well fed, warm and healthy.

148
00:19:42,304 --> 00:19:52,358
It's quite another thing to be able to believe that same fact and act upon it when we're cold and hungry, when someone pushes our buttons, insults us or assaults us.

149
00:19:54,942 --> 00:19:58,867
Meditation practice opens many avenues for such wisdom.

150
00:19:59,641 --> 00:20:02,526
One comes from seeing how much anger hurts us.

151
00:20:03,607 --> 00:20:11,222
We learn this when we have the patience to sit still with angry thoughts and open up to the full experience of the emotional storm.

152
00:20:12,705 --> 00:20:15,590
Tensions develop in various parts of the body.

153
00:20:15,570 --> 00:20:20,160
Our thoughts tighten us into a knot of self-righteousness and blame.

154
00:20:21,222 --> 00:20:25,592
We explode into rage or shrink into a livid pot of hatred.

155
00:20:26,594 --> 00:20:29,700
Eventually though the emotion burns itself out.

156
00:20:31,403 --> 00:20:35,992
As it does so we sense the hurt linking beneath our anger.

157
00:20:37,238 --> 00:20:39,921
That hurt is what really needs acknowledgement.

158
00:20:41,201 --> 00:20:47,367
Once we've done so, our thoughts become more rational and we somehow come to terms with the situation.

159
00:20:48,690 --> 00:20:53,634
On reflection, we see that the bout of anger had been deepening the hurt within ourselves.

160
00:20:54,655 --> 00:20:57,077
It hadn't done anything to help the situation.

161
00:20:59,820 --> 00:21:03,464
The more often we sit through anger and feel its raw energy,

162
00:21:03,901 --> 00:21:10,490
the less easily are we seduced by its appealing thoughts of vengeance and glorious triumph over our opponents.

163
00:21:12,233 --> 00:21:20,605
One very easy mistake to make is to denounce ourselves for anger and suppress all its energy, persuading ourselves we're not really angry.

164
00:21:22,288 --> 00:21:24,271
We need to find the middle way.

165
00:21:24,606 --> 00:21:35,987
feeling the anger, acknowledging it, relaxing right into the heart of it, but dropping the thoughts and beliefs it suggests moment after moment, thought after thought.

166
00:21:37,249 --> 00:21:47,846
This way we learn to appreciate the raw energy stimulated by aversion, the way it straightens our spine, makes us razor sharp alert.

167
00:21:50,037 --> 00:21:56,125
Dropping the thoughts prompted by ill-will, this raw energy can be channeled into assertiveness.

168
00:21:58,267 --> 00:22:08,941
The strong sense of self stimulated by aversion is then free to think friendly thoughts of goodwill and compassion without an unhelpful peppering of hatred or ill-will.

169
00:22:11,784 --> 00:22:15,588
A word about aversion and the wisdom that can be associated with.

170
00:22:17,711 --> 00:22:28,683
Aversion becomes a hindrance when we identify with it, clinging to thoughts like, you're bad, you're wrong, and building up a mental case to justify all this.

171
00:22:30,924 --> 00:22:38,955
Our practice with anger, ill-will, resentment and all the other emotions stimulated by aversion helps us drop the identification.

172
00:22:40,518 --> 00:22:44,743
But the basic discernment of an unpleasant situation can still be registered.

173
00:22:45,766 --> 00:22:50,352
The difference is that we can now act on this dispassionately.

174
00:22:51,394 --> 00:23:05,951
Going back to the welfare office example, we register the unpleasant implications of our file having been lost, that we won't have any money coming in, the burden having to find all our documents, write to previous employers and so on.

175
00:23:06,833 --> 00:23:09,576
There's also the disappointment that the system has failed.

176
00:23:10,817 --> 00:23:13,401
All of these are valid judgments of the situation.

177
00:23:14,142 --> 00:23:17,705
They're a part of the truth that needs to be acknowledged.

178
00:23:19,626 --> 00:23:24,673
So aversion in the sense of recognizing an unpleasant feeling or situation is not a problem.

179
00:23:26,215 --> 00:23:31,844
The Buddha registered aversion when he first thought about teaching others the way to enlightenment.

180
00:23:31,864 --> 00:23:37,491
He reflected that it would simply leave him vexed because the truth was too subtle for others to understand.

181
00:23:37,551 --> 00:23:49,228
As the story goes, he needed to be persuaded by the god Brahma that some people had but little dust in their eyes and would be able to follow his lead to enlightenment.

182
00:23:50,238 --> 00:23:57,247
Realising there was some point to the undertaking he could then frame any vexation as worthy within the overall picture.

183
00:23:59,029 --> 00:24:07,300
This allowed him to say many years later that when people rejected his teaching he experienced equanimity.

184
00:24:08,542 --> 00:24:19,096
He could register the unwelcome fact that they were rejecting what he held dear and instead choosing dukkha but could then let them go their own way in peace.

185
00:24:20,561 --> 00:24:29,592
Wisdom allows aversive situations to be known as unfortunate, unpleasant, unwanted, but embraced with equanimity.

186
00:24:32,454 --> 00:24:35,678
Wisdom is also what saves us in the welfare office.

187
00:24:36,779 --> 00:24:46,349
To the extent that we've taken the truth of dukkha on board, we know that everything is unreliable, that everything and everyone fails sooner or later.

188
00:24:47,224 --> 00:24:50,128
We know that reacting against this makes things worse.

189
00:24:51,171 --> 00:24:54,615
We know that the way through difficulties is to embrace them fully.

190
00:24:55,616 --> 00:24:58,780
So we don't take the situation as a personal insult or loss.

191
00:24:59,502 --> 00:25:02,226
We embrace it as a step on our path of enlightenment.

192
00:25:04,269 --> 00:25:13,182
Wisdom accrues from seeing the three characteristics, anicca or transience, anatta or not-self and dukkha, suffering.

193
00:25:14,528 --> 00:25:22,699
Experiencing and reflecting upon the transient, ephemeral nature of all experience, we gradually disentangle ourselves from dukkha.

194
00:25:24,020 --> 00:25:35,457
We see how identifying with our feelings and emotions intensifies their power, how the mind concocts stories out of nothing, creates mountains out of molehills.

195
00:25:37,073 --> 00:25:47,672
When we see through the false identity, the once powerful emotion reveals itself as a mass of sensations and feelings without any coherent rationale.

196
00:25:49,275 --> 00:25:51,759
What was the point of clinging to all that, we wonder?

197
00:25:53,321 --> 00:26:00,094
The absence of a storyline becomes more appealing than our usual insistence on rehashing our point of view.

198
00:26:01,761 --> 00:26:09,111
Something about the quiet spaces between sensations, thoughts and mind states starts to call our attention.

199
00:26:10,692 --> 00:26:14,958
We feel ourselves more and more attracted to that absence of drama.

200
00:26:16,200 --> 00:26:24,130
And for its sake we become increasingly willing to let go of our usual desire for pleasure, for things going my way.

201
00:26:26,393 --> 00:26:29,135
We might not be able to put any words to this wisdom.

202
00:26:30,195 --> 00:26:33,118
It's a loosening of the ties that bind us to suffering.

203
00:26:34,401 --> 00:26:39,446
It is expressed not so much in words but as a way of interacting with the world.

204
00:26:40,508 --> 00:26:48,877
We're more willing to experience life at the level of basic sensation than through the veil of our interpretations and ideas.

205
00:26:50,720 --> 00:26:57,047
This loosens the absolutist black and white stance we so often adopt in challenging situations.

206
00:26:58,174 --> 00:27:05,444
Instead of acting out habitual behaviour patterns again and again, we're looking for the escape route, the way back to peace.

207
00:27:06,926 --> 00:27:10,270
Our muscles relax a bit easier in stressful situations.

208
00:27:11,231 --> 00:27:15,357
Our emotions become more apparent and thereby less overpowering.

209
00:27:16,699 --> 00:27:24,789
As our emotional armour cracks, whispers of thoughts like, it never pays to act out of anger, can be registered.

210
00:27:25,833 --> 00:27:32,361
We might find ourselves clinging to the thought for dear life as a storm of rage blasts us with its fury.

211
00:27:34,943 --> 00:27:37,166
Wisdom is what suggests the thought.

212
00:27:37,847 --> 00:27:39,650
It never pays to act out of anger.

213
00:27:41,172 --> 00:27:46,518
Faith keeps our hearts up as the storm of anger counters with the barrage of objections.

214
00:27:47,138 --> 00:27:48,420
Of course I should be angry.

215
00:27:48,800 --> 00:27:49,942
I need to be angry.

216
00:27:50,603 --> 00:27:53,967
He'll walk all over me unless I let fly and so on.

217
00:27:54,992 --> 00:27:58,497
Our problem is that we don't know how to make good of the situation.

218
00:27:59,657 --> 00:28:05,845
So wisdom has nothing more to offer other than its original suggestion, acting out of anger won't help.

219
00:28:06,885 --> 00:28:10,289
When wisdom runs out, faith steps into the breach.

220
00:28:14,294 --> 00:28:16,336
The Pali word for faith is Sata.

221
00:28:17,376 --> 00:28:19,640
This can also be translated as confidence.

222
00:28:20,941 --> 00:28:23,463
We're not talking here about blind faith in dogma.

223
00:28:23,932 --> 00:28:30,320
we're talking about a heartfelt trust in what inspires our confidence.

224
00:28:30,340 --> 00:28:35,146
At the start of our spiritual journey, we place our faith in whatever spark got us going.

225
00:28:36,188 --> 00:28:39,913
It may have been something we read or someone who inspired us to give it a try.

226
00:28:40,933 --> 00:28:51,527
It may just have been a hunch or even desperation, sensing that there must be something other than the world of indulgence, individuality, success and failure.

227
00:28:51,507 --> 00:28:56,513
That initial inspiration or desperation can be very powerful.

228
00:28:57,375 --> 00:29:02,061
It gives us the energy to seek out a teacher, a retreat, a meditation group.

229
00:29:02,962 --> 00:29:05,405
It gets us started on our spiritual quest.

230
00:29:07,269 --> 00:29:09,991
In time, however, the initial brightness fades.

231
00:29:10,913 --> 00:29:12,957
The teacher doesn't seem so alluring.

232
00:29:13,517 --> 00:29:14,377
Retreats are tough.

233
00:29:15,319 --> 00:29:17,682
People in the meditation group start to annoy us.

234
00:29:18,912 --> 00:29:21,875
Our disappointment crystallises as doubt.

235
00:29:23,417 --> 00:29:27,884
Unless we've learned to recognise and work with doubt, we'll give up at this point.

236
00:29:28,885 --> 00:29:35,596
We could go off in search of another path, a more inspiring teacher, a more congenial meditation group.

237
00:29:36,998 --> 00:29:44,228
But the same pattern of inspiration followed by disappointment will repeat itself until we learn to work through our doubts.

238
00:29:45,348 --> 00:29:47,873
As we do so, faith develops.

239
00:29:50,063 --> 00:29:52,709
At times, doubt can turn to self-doubt.

240
00:29:53,791 --> 00:29:58,261
We think that we're too dim-witted or too self-centered or too angry.

241
00:29:58,923 --> 00:30:02,992
And that's why the Dhamma doesn't seem to be making any impact on our lives.

242
00:30:04,339 --> 00:30:06,824
Again, the spectre has to be embraced.

243
00:30:07,924 --> 00:30:11,691
The certainties, too dim-witted, no impact, etc.

244
00:30:12,070 --> 00:30:17,599
need to be examined mindfully as part of our present experience.

245
00:30:17,619 --> 00:30:20,903
What other aspects of experience can we notice?

246
00:30:20,923 --> 00:30:21,945
Tensions perhaps?

247
00:30:22,946 --> 00:30:25,371
Emotions like despair or self-hatred?

248
00:30:26,712 --> 00:30:29,257
Can we muster the energy to sit through these?

249
00:30:30,417 --> 00:30:32,862
Would it help to talk with a friend or a teacher?

250
00:30:33,769 --> 00:30:49,602
All teachers will have come through such trials, and may be able to encourage you to embrace the spectre of self-doubt, trusting that, like all spectres, it will at times dissolve into thin air, leaving you wondering, what was that all about?

251
00:30:52,567 --> 00:31:04,006
As we work our way mindfully through the hindrances, our initial bright faith transforms to a deep, heartfelt confidence in ourselves and in the path we have chosen.

252
00:31:06,048 --> 00:31:08,011
Faith and wisdom work hand in hand.

253
00:31:09,375 --> 00:31:12,378
Wisdom represents our understanding of the Dhamma.

254
00:31:13,441 --> 00:31:16,045
Faith represents our willingness to embrace it.

255
00:31:17,222 --> 00:31:22,469
Faith is energising, heartfelt, a joyous movement towards truth.

256
00:31:24,411 --> 00:31:29,236
Wisdom discerns the dukkha of clinging and persuades us to let go.

257
00:31:29,256 --> 00:31:36,924
Without wisdom, we would cling to faith, become a zealot, insisting on our dogma.

258
00:31:38,386 --> 00:31:45,153
Without faith, wisdom gets stuck in detail rather than taking the scary step into the unknown.

259
00:31:46,821 --> 00:31:57,836
When the two are working in tandem, wisdom asks us to choose the middle way, to abandon reactivity and loosen our clutch on habitual patterns.

260
00:31:58,979 --> 00:32:08,711
Faith heartens us in this unfamiliar territory, lets us trust that some beneficial way forward will emerge.

261
00:32:10,784 --> 00:32:23,847
Thus, wisdom and faith, along with the other spiritual faculties of mindfulness, concentration and energy, can steer us through our bout of rage that emerges in the welfare office.

262
00:32:25,819 --> 00:32:28,262
There's no saying how the situation will unfold.

263
00:32:29,484 --> 00:32:33,750
After a few seconds of gallant resistance, anger might break through anyhow.

264
00:32:33,790 --> 00:32:41,621
Or we might become confused, unable to deal with the situation at all, as the next person in the queue shoves us out of the way.

265
00:32:42,261 --> 00:32:43,523
We might break down and cry.

266
00:32:43,564 --> 00:32:46,748
Or we might find something useful to say.

267
00:32:47,520 --> 00:32:58,135
No matter what happens, we've made an attempt to break an old habit in a very challenging situation, and that will stand to us greatly in spiritual terms.

268
00:33:00,558 --> 00:33:08,190
I had some strange experiences the first few times I consciously tried to break unskillful communication habits in conflict situations.

269
00:33:09,832 --> 00:33:15,519
My natural habit is to withdraw, say nothing, but be privately disgusted with the other person.

270
00:33:16,900 --> 00:33:22,204
The first time I found the courage to say something in protest, I ended up speaking nonsense.

271
00:33:22,905 --> 00:33:28,009
I couldn't understand what I was saying myself, never mind expecting the other person to make sense of it.

272
00:33:29,612 --> 00:33:37,338
I then had to endure my adversary saying, calm down, love, let me explain, as he summarily dismissed every basis for my complaint.

273
00:33:38,180 --> 00:33:39,540
So that didn't work out too well.

274
00:33:40,642 --> 00:33:45,826
But it showed me the magnitude of the task I was facing in learning a new habit of assertiveness.

275
00:33:47,950 --> 00:33:51,441
The next time I tried was when someone was giving me a blast of their anger.

276
00:33:52,423 --> 00:34:01,250
Although I felt cowed and wanted to withdraw into a disgusted silence, I knew I should change the pattern, say something to stand up for myself.

277
00:34:02,175 --> 00:34:04,258
Again what came out was pure nonsense.

278
00:34:04,818 --> 00:34:06,580
It wasn't even an English sentence.

279
00:34:07,682 --> 00:34:12,706
After a few seconds I found myself apologising, saying, I don't know what I'm trying to say.

280
00:34:12,746 --> 00:34:16,952
But this time my incoherence had the desired effect.

281
00:34:17,932 --> 00:34:24,719
My adversary, probably sensing my distress, calmed down and apologised for his own outburst of anger.

282
00:34:25,961 --> 00:34:30,867
We were then able to talk rationally about the problem and come to an amicable agreement.

283
00:34:34,389 --> 00:34:38,454
so we needn't expect our spiritual life to unfold in a dignified way.

284
00:34:40,315 --> 00:34:49,023
But somehow our unskillful habits change for the better and we become more able to address life's challenges and appreciate its beauties.

285
00:34:50,844 --> 00:35:01,494
To finish, I'd like to recap on the qualities we're developing here on retreat and how these link with the spiritual faculties which we need for everyday life.

286
00:35:04,259 --> 00:35:08,443
In Vipassana we are developing the seven factors of enlightenment.

287
00:35:10,025 --> 00:35:18,896
The three leading factors of mindfulness, concentration and energy become habits that we can take into our ordinary lives.

288
00:35:20,978 --> 00:35:27,987
Mindfulness anchors our attention in reality, saves us from daydreaming or worrying our lives away.

289
00:35:28,880 --> 00:35:36,472
Sights, sounds and all our sense data become meaningful experiences in which our busy minds can rest and recuperate.

290
00:35:38,213 --> 00:35:46,206
This grounding in reality gives us some objectivity on the baggage we bring into stressful situations and thereby the possibility of letting go.

291
00:35:46,246 --> 00:35:56,742
The faculty of concentration focuses our attention on the task at hand, lets us become more effective in our lives rather than scattered and superficial.

292
00:35:58,141 --> 00:36:06,472
The faculty of energy gives us the wherewithal to breast the current of unskillful habits and swim upstream with our skillful ones.

293
00:36:08,695 --> 00:36:13,242
The next factors developed in Vipassana are investigation and equanimity.

294
00:36:14,224 --> 00:36:17,347
Their benefit shows up within the faculty of wisdom.

295
00:36:18,896 --> 00:36:28,677
As we investigate our experience in Vipassana, it sinks in ever deeper that greed, hatred and delusion hurt us in many ways.

296
00:36:30,202 --> 00:36:38,559
We bring that wisdom with us into daily life where it persuades us not to act out old habits of suffering.

297
00:36:40,597 --> 00:36:46,550
With equanimity, wisdom gets some weight and can steady us through a storm of passion.

298
00:36:47,652 --> 00:36:52,762
The thought, it never pays to act out of anger, is only a fleeting thought.

299
00:36:53,885 --> 00:37:00,378
As already mentioned, anger will immediately counter with arguments like, he'll walk all over me unless I blow my top.

300
00:37:02,923 --> 00:37:12,373
We can feel the attraction towards these thoughts, the strong, powerful sense of self they conjure up, the sweet sensations they release in our bodies.

301
00:37:13,655 --> 00:37:22,222
Our certainty that anger doesn't help will be shattered unless equanimity steadies us against anger's counter-revolution.

302
00:37:24,125 --> 00:37:32,052
While wisdom relates mainly to our rational mind, the faculty of faith is based in feeling rather than the intellect.

303
00:37:33,686 --> 00:37:36,371
It is a heartfelt confidence in our path.

304
00:37:37,913 --> 00:37:44,782
Thus, it relates closely to the final pair in the factors of enlightenment, joy and tranquility.

305
00:37:46,346 --> 00:37:52,675
To the extent that we've developed joy in Vipassana, our hearts will be open to the joy of faith.

306
00:37:53,869 --> 00:37:57,878
We will be glad to have a practice we can trust, a path to follow.

307
00:37:58,800 --> 00:38:05,074
Joy lifts the spirit, lets us become more confident in ourselves and in our chosen path.

308
00:38:06,257 --> 00:38:08,300
It gives momentum to our faith.

309
00:38:10,659 --> 00:38:18,010
The spiritual path leads us toward quiet waters where we're asked to surrender much of what we normally prize.

310
00:38:18,951 --> 00:38:20,293
Pleasure and stimulation.

311
00:38:21,295 --> 00:38:22,956
Striving to get on top of things.

312
00:38:23,657 --> 00:38:24,398
Being noticed.

313
00:38:25,019 --> 00:38:25,860
Being a success.

314
00:38:27,001 --> 00:38:28,264
Having a story to tell.

315
00:38:29,965 --> 00:38:39,199
We're going against the values of our culture here and this would really test our faith unless we develop a degree of tranquility in Vipassana.

316
00:38:40,579 --> 00:38:55,523
If we can appreciate quiet moments where nothing is achieved, savour the absence of drama, enjoy listening as well as speaking, then our spiritual life can flourish even within the busyness of modern culture.

317
00:38:57,005 --> 00:39:04,376
To let us appreciate the absence of achievement, the absence of excitement, we have the delight of tranquillity.

318
00:39:05,588 --> 00:39:11,077
This delight strengthens our faith in a life of surrender and renunciation.

319
00:39:14,724 --> 00:39:27,545
May our meditation practice here on retreat strengthen the spiritual faculties so that every aspect of ordinary daily life becomes part of our path to enlightenment.

